{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17510895","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17510895"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:34:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:34:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11659"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11659","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11659"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.24,0.17,0.14,0.43]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4280"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98677"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4280","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4280"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11659"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"81064"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"339"},{"type":"tags","id":"1155"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"9222"},{"type":"tags","id":"9478"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5755"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7528"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26971"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33791"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98677","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/98677"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 76-year-old woman from a residential care home presents to the Emergency Department with a one-week history of a painful swelling in front of her left ear (Image). Her nurse indicates she has refused oral intake for the past two days. She has a medical history of congestive cardiac failure and hypertension. Her medications include furosemide (recently increased), ramipril, and spironolactone. She has no known allergies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 38.2\u00b0C. The swelling is warm to touch, tender and fluctuant. She is unable to open her mouth more than 2 centimetres and has difficulty breathing while lying flat.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Warm compresses","Intravenous flucloxacillin","Ultrasound-guided aspiration","Parotid duct decompression","Incision and drainage"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a parotid abscess, likely precipitated by dehydration from increased diuretic therapy. The clinical features supporting this diagnosis include the location of the swelling, fever, trismus, and a fluctuant, tender mass. The patient\u0027s systemic symptoms (fever, tachycardia) and functional impairment (inability to eat, difficulty breathing when supine) indicate a severe infection requiring urgent intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGiven the difficulty in laying down, difficulty opening the mouth and reduced oral intake, \u003Cstrong\u003Eincision and drainage\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate option due to the urgency of the presentation. This provides immediate decompression, relieves pain, and allows for bacterial culture to guide antibiotic therapy. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWarm compresses\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eparotid duct decompression\u003C/strong\u003E are not viable options as an abscess is an encased collection and has no path to drain from. Parotid duct compression might be useful for managing obstructive sialadenitis or sialolithiasis, but once an abscess has formed, the purulent collection is walled off from the ductal system and requires direct drainage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUltrasound-guided aspiration\u003C/strong\u003E may be useful for temporary symptom relief but without appropriate washout there is the chance of recurrence. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGiven the severity of the presentation, \u003Cstrong\u003Eintravenous flucloxacillin \u003C/strong\u003Ewould not work rapidly enough to reduce symptoms. In a patient with a milder presentation, intravenous antibiotics may be considered as conservative management prior to incision and drainage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EParotid abscess, once a relatively common post-operative complication, is now rare.\u00a0 It tends to occur in debilitated patients who have become dehydrated and have reduced salivary flow.\u00a0 Parotid duct obstruction secondary to a stone is another cause of abscess formation.\u00a0 When draining the abscess, care must be taken to avoid damage to the facial nerve.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAs it has once been said \u0022\u003Cem\u003EUbi pus, ibi evacua\u0022 (\u003C/em\u003ELatin medical aphorism meaning \u0022where there is pus, there evacuate it\u0022).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Parotid abscess requires incision and drainage when there is evidence of significant infection with systemic symptoms.","Dehydration from diuretic use is a risk factor for parotid gland infection in elderly patients.","Trismus and respiratory difficulty are concerning signs in parotid infections that warrant urgent intervention."],"references":["Srivanitchapoom C, Yata K. Clinical characteristics that predict parotid abscess: An observational cohort study. Ann Med Surg (Lond). 2021 Mar 16;64:102230. doi: 10.1016/j.amsu.2021.102230. PMID: 33777393; PMCID: PMC7985271. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33777393/","Chang BA, Thamboo A, Burton MJ, Diamond C, Nunez DA. Needle aspiration versus incision and drainage for the treatment of peritonsillar abscess. Cochrane Database Syst Rev. 2016 Dec 23;12(12):CD006287. doi: 10.1002/14651858.CD006287.pub4. PMID: 28009937; PMCID: PMC6463807. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28009937/","Saibene AM, Allevi F, Ayad T, Lechien JR, Mayo-Y\u00e1\u00f1ez M, Piersiala K, Chiesa-Estomba CM. Treatment for parotid abscess: a systematic review. Acta Otorhinolaryngol Ital. 2022 Apr;42(2):106-115. doi: 10.14639/0392-100X-N1837. PMID: 35612503; PMCID: PMC9132006. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9132006/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"81064"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11659"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18399"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18399","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18399"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/324872e9-9aad-49ae-8f74-aab88f30e712.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/324872e9-9aad-49ae-8f74-aab88f30e712.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"81064","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/81064"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-16T12:02:08+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-16T12:03:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4280"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98677"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.